<paragraph id="8BB60445FFFA627EFF141F1E20DC8DE5" blockId="4.[136,1059,1303,1423]" pageId="4" pageNumber="643">REMARKS: The medially directed projections arising from the costal edge of the valvae posterad from the dorsal articulations of the valvae with the vinculum are not called a transtilla as the definition of this structure is restricted to â€˜the [dorsal] sclerotisation of the diaphragmaâ€™ (Solis &amp; Maes, 2003).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB60445FFFA627FFF141FA820F68AB0" blockId="4.[136,1059,1441,1658]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1074,227,1659]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="644" pageId="4" pageNumber="643">
SYSTEMATIC POSITION: The current classification of Neotropical 
<taxonomicName id="4C097FC6FFFA627EFC561FA823388DB2" authority="(Munroe, 1995)" baseAuthorityName="Munroe" baseAuthorityYear="1995" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Spilomelinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="643" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
Spilomelinae (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9879B4FFFA627EFF511FCB23338DB2" author="MUNROE, E. G." box="[145,305,1473,1497]" pageId="4" pageNumber="643" pagination="53 - 79" refId="ref6215" refString="MUNROE, E. G. 1995. Pyraustinae (pp. 53 - 79). In: Heppner, J. B. (ed.), Atlas of Neotropical Lepidoptera, Volume 3. Association for Tropical Lepidoptera and Scientific Publishers, Gainesville." type="book chapter" year="1995">Munroe, 1995</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
recognizes 14 groups of genera and 51 unplaced genera. Unfortunately, Munroe did not provide diagnostic characters to support his groups, and there is no classification available for any other Spilomelinae fauna. Therefore, we examined representatives of Munroe's generic groups to find apparently diagnostic character combinations, and we comment on their validity and applicability to the newly described genus. 
<taxonomicName id="4C097FC6FFFA627EFE4B1C6823FD8E12" authorityName="Landry" authorityYear="2011" box="[395,511,1633,1657]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Cheverella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="643" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFA627EFE4B1C6823FD8E12" box="[395,511,1633,1657]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="643">Cheverella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found to have affinities with the 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFA627EFC5A1C6821F68E12" box="[922,1012,1633,1657]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="643">Hydriris</emphasis>
and the 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFF041AEA22F18891" box="[196,243,227,250]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Siga</emphasis>
groups of 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9879B4FFFB627FFEB81AED20228890" author="MUNROE, E. G." box="[376,544,227,251]" pageId="5" pageNumber="644" pagination="53 - 79" refId="ref6215" refString="MUNROE, E. G. 1995. Pyraustinae (pp. 53 - 79). In: Heppner, J. B. (ed.), Atlas of Neotropical Lepidoptera, Volume 3. Association for Tropical Lepidoptera and Scientific Publishers, Gainesville." type="book chapter" year="1995">Munroe (1995)</bibRefCitation>
. With the Hydriris group, 
<taxonomicName id="4C097FC6FFFB627FFC961AEA21C88890" authorityName="Landry" authorityYear="2011" box="[854,970,227,251]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Cheverella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFC961AEA21C88890" box="[854,970,227,251]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Cheverella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares a reduced uncus without robust bifid spines and the presence of setose pads in the vicinity of the transtilla in 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFE5A1B2A203C8950" box="[410,574,291,315]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Choristostigma</emphasis>
Warren. However, in the other genera of the group, the setose pads are in different positions (on the costa in 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFC911B4A21A08930" box="[849,930,323,347]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Geshna</emphasis>
Dyar, on the tegumen in 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFED81B6A23708910" box="[280,370,355,379]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Hydriris</emphasis>
Meyrick) or absent in 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFDAD1B6A20DD8910" box="[621,735,355,379]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Nehydriris</emphasis>
Munroe. Most of the members of this group share tufts of setae at or around the base of the costa of the valva, but these setae are lacking in 
<taxonomicName id="4C097FC6FFFB627FFE7B1BAA202D89D0" authorityName="Landry" authorityYear="2011" box="[443,559,419,443]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Cheverella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFE7B1BAA202D89D0" box="[443,559,419,443]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Cheverella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFDAA1BAA20DE89D0" box="[618,732,419,443]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Nehydriris</emphasis>
, and the female genitalia vary among the three genera for which they are known. The Diagnosis above explains some of the differences between the female genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C097FC6FFFB627FFD151BEA214B8990" authorityName="Landry" authorityYear="2011" box="[725,841,483,507]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Cheverella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFD151BEA214B8990" box="[725,841,483,507]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Cheverella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFC461BEA26288990" box="[902,1066,483,507]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Choristostigma</emphasis>
. Those of 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFF3B180A234E8A70" box="[251,332,515,539]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Geshna</emphasis>
show a poorly differentiated, elongate corpus bursae without signum, while those of 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFEF6182A23928A50" box="[310,400,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Hydriris</emphasis>
have a very short ductus bursae and an elongate corpus bursae with an appendix bursae and with two large signa showing about 12 long, thin and curved projections. The labial palpi are variable. They are upturned in 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFC67186A26038A10" box="[935,1025,611,635]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Hydriris</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFF57188A22EA8AF0" box="[151,232,643,667]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Geshna</emphasis>
but porrect with downturned apical meron in 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFD15188A217B8AF0" box="[725,889,643,667]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Choristostigma</emphasis>
, so the upwardly directed palpi of 
<taxonomicName id="4C097FC6FFFB627FFE8B18AA23BD8AD0" authorityName="Landry" authorityYear="2011" box="[331,447,675,699]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Cheverella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFE8B18AA23BD8AD0" box="[331,447,675,699]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Cheverella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fit in this range. Hence, there is no clear indication that the 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFF5718CA22F38AB0" box="[151,241,707,731]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Hydriris</emphasis>
group is monophyletic as presently constituted.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB60445FFFB627FFF2318EA21598DF0" blockId="5.[151,1074,227,1659]" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">
The 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFED518EA23468A91" box="[277,324,739,762]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Siga</emphasis>
group of 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9879B4FFFB627FFE7218ED20548A90" author="MUNROE, E. G." box="[434,598,739,763]" pageId="5" pageNumber="644" pagination="53 - 79" refId="ref6215" refString="MUNROE, E. G. 1995. Pyraustinae (pp. 53 - 79). In: Heppner, J. B. (ed.), Atlas of Neotropical Lepidoptera, Volume 3. Association for Tropical Lepidoptera and Scientific Publishers, Gainesville." type="book chapter" year="1995">Munroe (1995)</bibRefCitation>
comprises large, robust-bodied Neotropical moths. Our concept of the group is here informed by our addition of 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFC69190A26338B70" box="[937,1073,771,795]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Loxomorpha</emphasis>
Amsel and 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFED6192D23898B50" box="[278,395,804,827]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Maracayia</emphasis>
Amsel, because they share the same structural characters and known larval habits, despite their much smaller size. So defined, the 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFCB7194A21A48B31" box="[887,934,835,858]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Siga</emphasis>
group varies greatly in maculation, but the forewing postmedial line is usually roundly concave on the anal fold. The labial palpi are short or obliquely ascending with a short apical meron. The male genitalia are robust with a moderately inflated sacculus and wellsclerotized costa, and the saccus is absent or weakly developed. The sella is aciculate in most member taxa (as in the 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFE3919EA20518B90" box="[505,595,995,1019]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Hydriris</emphasis>
group), but it is quadrate in some (
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFC2019EA23028C70" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Cirrhocephalina</emphasis>
Munroe) or with a basal process (
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFDBF1E0A20E08C70" box="[639,738,1027,1051]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Laniifera</emphasis>
Hampson). The uncus is bifid with a short stalk or none at all (with the two uncus arms arising from the tegumen separately), and the apices of the uncus are armed with robust, bifid chaetae. In the female genitalia, where known, the ostium bursae is strongly sclerotized and shaped like a funnel or pitcher plant, and the corpus bursae lacks a signum. Known larvae (
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFF601EAA23018CD0" box="[160,259,1187,1211]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Laniifera</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFED71EAA23678CD0" box="[279,357,1187,1211]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Beebea</emphasis>
Schaus, 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFE121EAA20588CD0" box="[466,602,1187,1211]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Loxomorpha</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFDAD1EAD20E08CD0" box="[621,738,1188,1211]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Maracayia</emphasis>
) are all borers in Cactaceae. Among these characters, 
<taxonomicName id="4C097FC6FFFB627FFE661ECA20188CB0" authorityName="Landry" authorityYear="2011" box="[422,538,1219,1243]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Cheverella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFE661ECA20188CB0" box="[422,538,1219,1243]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Cheverella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares the straight and obliquely ascending labial palpi, robust genitalia with inflated sacculus, and the distally quadrate sella of some members. The breadth of the ostium bursae is similar, but it is only weakly sclerotized in 
<taxonomicName id="4C097FC6FFFB627FFF761F2A23288D50" authorityName="Landry" authorityYear="2011" box="[182,298,1315,1339]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Cheverella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFF761F2A23288D50" box="[182,298,1315,1339]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Cheverella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The absence of an uncus, bifid or otherwise, would be explained as derived from the reduced bilobate condition seen in 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFD141F4A21638D30" box="[724,865,1347,1371]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Zeuzerobotys</emphasis>
Munroe. Although 
<taxonomicName id="4C097FC6FFFB627FFF571F6A23098D10" authorityName="Landry" authorityYear="2011" box="[151,267,1379,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Cheverella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFF571F6A23098D10" box="[151,267,1379,1403]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Cheverella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is much smaller than most, it is comparable in size to 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFC8F1F6A21D58D10" box="[847,983,1379,1403]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Loxomorpha</emphasis>
species. The black and white wing coloration is shared with 
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFD061F8A21518DF0" box="[710,851,1411,1435]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Zeuzerobotys</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB60445FFFB627FFF231FAA23F48E10" blockId="5.[151,1074,227,1659]" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">
The following characters are shared by the two groups and 
<taxonomicName id="4C097FC6FFFB627FFC531FAA26058DD0" authorityName="Landry" authorityYear="2011" box="[915,1031,1443,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Cheverella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFC531FAA26058DD0" box="[915,1031,1443,1467]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Cheverella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, so although they do not favor placement in either group, they exclude 
<taxonomicName id="4C097FC6FFFB627FFC401FCA21F68DB0" authorityName="Landry" authorityYear="2011" box="[896,1012,1475,1499]" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Cheverella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="644" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97DD857FFFB627FFC401FCA21F68DB0" box="[896,1012,1475,1499]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="644">Cheverella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from many other spilomeline groups. The valve costa is straight or slightly concave, and the apex of the valve is rounded but attenuate (narrower than the valve width across the costa). The valve sella originates variably from the costal half of the valve or near middle of the valve. The hindwing maculation is nearly absent, and the praecinctorium is weakly (not strongly) bilobed.
</paragraph>
